article.description: Katie Smith scored 33 points to lead the Minnesota Lynx to a 63-60 win Sunday night over Phoenix, sending the Mercury to their fifth straight loss.
article.headline: Smith drops 33 on slumping Mercury
article.linkText: Katie Smith leads Lynx to 7th win in eight games
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP)-- The Minnesota Lynx know who to get the ball to
when the game is on the line -- Katie Smith.

	   Smith scored six points in the final minute and finished with
33, one off her career best, to lead the Lynx to a 63-60 victory
over the Phoenix Mercury on Sunday night.

	   "She's being aggressive. And this team feeds off of that,"
Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "They get going when
Katie gets going. It's makes it easier for this team when Katie
gets going."

	   Minnesota won its fifth straight and moved within two games of
first place in the Western Conference.

	   Penny Taylor scored 20 points and had 10 rebounds and three
assists for the Mercury, who have lost five straight and seven of
nine.

	   Smith, who had 19 points in the second half, hit two baskets and
a pair of free throws in the final minute for the Lynx, who have
won seven of eight.

	   Phoenix missed two 3-pointers in the final nine seconds.

	   "Katie Smith hit huge shots for us down the stretch,"
McConnell Serio said. "She is someone we want to have the ball in
her hands. She made her free throws and she's done it over and over
for us. She did it again tonight."

	   Smith has averaged 21 points a game during the winning streak,
including a 34-point outing against Sacramento on July 11, and is
the fifth leading scorer in the league at 18 per game.

	   "I had some good looks at the bucket," said Smith, who was
11-for-18 from the field. "We moved the ball, we executed.
Everybody has been stepping up big during our stretch right now. We
have been able to knock down shots when we've needed to."

	   Phoenix coach Carrie Graf called Smith a "world class player."

	   "She got away from us and we didn't defend her well down the
stretch. We didn't have an answer for her tonight," Graf said.

	   The Lynx, the worst shooting team in the WNBA, overcame 39
percent shooting (21-for-54) to beat Phoenix for the third time in
four meetings.

	   Phoenix rookie Diana Taurasi, the third leading scorer in the
WNBA, scored 15 points on 6-for-15 shooting.

	   Lynx rookie Nicole Ohlde had 11 points and seven rebounds while
Tamika Williams added 10 points and eight rebounds.

	   The Mercury trailed 57-55 with 1:15 left when Taylor missed an
open jump shot and Smith answered with a 17-footer. Smith added an
18-footer with 25 seconds left and two free throws with 15 seconds
remaining.

	   "She made big shot after big shot," said Taurasi. "We did not
do a good job on her at all."

	   Taurasi and Shereka Wright missed off-balance 3s in the final
possession.

	   The Lynx won the two meetings between the two teams in
Minneapolis, but lost the previous game in Phoenix.
